### [Visual] Jess looking consfused, trace list with fragmented `session.id` for the same user within what she wants as a defined session, and Meminator being refreshed in browser. Note on screen: This application has been instrumented with automatic instrumentation and [...if there is anything custom added, note it here]!
**[Audio]**  
Jess, a frontend engineer working on a web application called Meminator, has been using Honeycomb to trace user interactions. But when she searches for `session.id` in her traces, she notices something problematic: every time a user refreshes the page, Honeycomb shows a completely new session, making it challenging to track a user's complete journey. 

To fix this, Jess needs to implement a proper session definition. For Meminator, she defines a session as follows: when a user first visits the app, they get a unique `session.id` that persists until either they close the browser tab or they go idle for more than an hour without generating a meme. Once the session ends, the `session.id` is cleared, and the next time they visit, they'll get a fresh `session.id`.

### [Visual] Show Meminator on browser being refreshed w/ diagram/visual showing how session IDs are assigned by default with each page load, followed by "override" visual cue to indicate defining option
**[Audio]**  
By default, the `HoneycombWebSDK` generates a new `session.id` every time the page loads. This means if a user clicks "GO" five times, refreshes the page, and clicks "GO" again, the sixth interaction will appear as completely separate, unrelated trace in Honeycomb—even though they're all part of the same user's session.

To get meaningful insights into user behavior, Jess needs to override this default session logic so her traces actually reflect how people use Meminator.

In this video, you'll learn how to implement define `session.id` with the `HoneycombWebSDK` to track user journeys the way that makes sense for your application. 

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

