By default, the `HoneycombWebSDK` generates a new `session.id` for every page load. This doesn't fit how user sessions actually work in Meminator. 

Instead, we can define our own logic using the `sessionProvider` property. Here's how...

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

### [Visual] Code snippet implementing a custom session ID using `sessionProvider` 
**[Audio]**  
First, we'll configure the `sessionProvider` property by implementing a `getSessionId` method. The SDK will then store this `session.id` in the browser's `sessionStorage` and reuse it across multiple "Go" clicks, page loads, and route changes, or generate a new one when needed.

```js
...
const sdk = new HoneycombWebSDK({
  apiKey: '[YOUR API KEY HERE]', 
  serviceName: '[YOUR SERVICE NAME HERE]', 
  ... // other config
  sessionProvider: {
      getSessionId: () => {
      return SessionGateway.getSession(); // this may require changes to the meminator app code and changes to the instrumentation code
      }
  }
// other config...
});

sdk.start();
```

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

### [Visual] Diagram showing custom session manager, `session.id` persists through various user actions inc. many meme generations, refreshing, and closing browser
**[Audio]**  
Now, what if your app needs to create new sessions based on user actions? Remember, for Meminator: we want sessions to end when users close their browser tab or go idle for more than an hour without generating a meme.

To implement this session logic, we need to actively manage when to clear the stored `session.id`—both when detecting that a user has been idle too long and when they close the browser tab.

Ending a session is straightforward—we simply remove the stored ID:

```js
...
const sdk = new HoneycombWebSDK({
  apiKey: '[YOUR API KEY HERE]', 
  serviceName: '[YOUR APPLICATION NAME HERE]', 
  ... // other config
  sessionProvider: {
      getSessionId: () => {
      return SessionGateway.getSession();
      },
      sessionStorage.removeItem('session.id'); // this also needs to be adjusted in the meminator app code? maybe?
  }
// other config...
});

sdk.start();
```

Here are some other common cases where expiring a session makes sense:
- A user goes from anonymous to logged in
- A user logs out
- A browser times out the session
- A user switches or assumes a new role

By explicitly clearing the stored `session.id`, you make sure Honeycomb data reflects accurate session boundaries.

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

